1.2 Pivot functions

library(here)
library(dplyr)
library(readr)

In the current lesson, we will learn about an important distinction when working with data namely the difference between long format and wide format.

In order to discuss the difference between the 2 data formats, we will upload the GBD and Gapminder dataframes that we already used in the previous lesson.

gapminder <- 
  read_csv(file = here("chapter_xxx_tidy_data/data/gapminder_hiv_full.csv"), show_col_types = FALSE)


GBD <- 
  read_csv(file = here("chapter_xxx_tidy_data/data/GBD_1.csv"), show_col_types = FALSE)

#we filter only the first 1000 rows to simplify the dataframe
GBD <- 
  GBD %>%
  select(-c(upper, lower)) %>%
  slice(1:1000)

Now, one of the 2 dataframes is in long format and the other in wide format. Try to guess based on their dimension.

If you think that GBD is in long and the Gapminder wide, you are right. Letâs define the concepts:

  • long format : there is a single column for each variable and the are as many rows as the combinations of those variables. For instance, if you look at the first 2 rows in the GDB dataframe you can notice that the only difference is in the categorical variable âsexâ, where the first row value refers to the males and the second to female individuals.

  • wide format : each variable is on a different column. In the gapminder dataframe you can see that the first column refers to a country and the following columns refer to the yearly HIV deaths

Overall, the wide format is easier to handle to visualize the data and for specific tasks like data entry. On the other hand, many tools in R studio work best when the data are in long format. One example is ggplot2, where the plots are simpler when the columns are in long format. Furthermore, databases are usually stored in long format because the way of storing the dataframes is unique and complete, while the wide format may represent multiple ways as we will see.

For these reasons, it is important to know how to convert between the 2 formats based on the task you are performing. The 2 functions that allow you to do that are the pivot functions are:

  • pivot_longer()

  • pivot_wider()

These 2 functions come with the package tidyr

#istall the package if you have not done it yet
#install.packages("tidyr")
library(tidyr)

1.2.1 pivot_longer

with pivot_longer() we can turn wide data into long format. We can test the function with gapminder data

gapminder_long <- 
  gapminder %>%
  pivot_longer(!country, names_to = "year", values_to = "deaths")

gapminder_long
## # A tibble: 3,278 x 3
##    country     year  deaths
##    <chr>       <chr> <chr> 
##  1 Afghanistan 1990  60    
##  2 Afghanistan 1991  60    
##  3 Afghanistan 1992  60    
##  4 Afghanistan 1993  60    
##  5 Afghanistan 1994  60    
##  6 Afghanistan 1995  150   
##  7 Afghanistan 1996  150   
##  8 Afghanistan 1997  150   
##  9 Afghanistan 1998  150   
## 10 Afghanistan 1999  150   
## # ... with 3,268 more rows

Letâs check step by step what we have done. Writing !country we tell to pivot_longer() to make long all the column but country. This is the easier solution but sometimes you may want to make your data long based on a subset of variables. In such cases, you can use the attribute cols and specify either the columns range by position or by name.

gapminder_long <- 
  gapminder %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = 2:23 , names_to = "year", values_to = "deaths")

gapminder_long
## # A tibble: 3,278 x 3
##    country     year  deaths
##    <chr>       <chr> <chr> 
##  1 Afghanistan 1990  60    
##  2 Afghanistan 1991  60    
##  3 Afghanistan 1992  60    
##  4 Afghanistan 1993  60    
##  5 Afghanistan 1994  60    
##  6 Afghanistan 1995  150   
##  7 Afghanistan 1996  150   
##  8 Afghanistan 1997  150   
##  9 Afghanistan 1998  150   
## 10 Afghanistan 1999  150   
## # ... with 3,268 more rows
gapminder_long <- 
  gapminder %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = "1990":"2011" , names_to = "year", values_to = "deaths")

gapminder_long
## # A tibble: 3,278 x 3
##    country     year  deaths
##    <chr>       <chr> <chr> 
##  1 Afghanistan 1990  60    
##  2 Afghanistan 1991  60    
##  3 Afghanistan 1992  60    
##  4 Afghanistan 1993  60    
##  5 Afghanistan 1994  60    
##  6 Afghanistan 1995  150   
##  7 Afghanistan 1996  150   
##  8 Afghanistan 1997  150   
##  9 Afghanistan 1998  150   
## 10 Afghanistan 1999  150   
## # ... with 3,268 more rows

the attribute names_to simply defines the new variable names and (in this case is âyearâ) and values_to defines the variable name where the values are stored

1.2.2 pivot_wider

now we can try to make the GBD data longer using pivot_wider. As we mentioned above, long format is unique while for wide data we can reshape the dataframe in multiple way. Letâs try to make wide the variable âcauseâ i.e.Â every cause is on a separate column

GBD_wide <- 
  GBD %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = "cause",
              values_from = "val")

The only two attributes that we need here are names_from, where we specify the variables we want to make wide, and values_from i.e.Â the column where the values will be stored (val in this example). When there are multiple variables, those that are not inside the argument names_from will not be turned wide e.g.Â GBD_wide still shows the variables âmeasureâ, âlocationâ, âsexâ, âmetricâ and âyearâ. Important, the argument names_from can take multiple variables allowing you to create more complicated nested tables. Letâs try to use both âcauseâ and âsexâ variables

GBD_wide <- 
  GBD %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = c("cause", "sex"),
               values_from = "val")

1.3 Tidy verbs

We will see 2 last functions that are defined as tidy verbs:

  • separate()

  • unite()

Note that many online resources still report as tidy verbs gather() and spread(). These 2 functions are actually deprecated and replaced by the 2 pivot functions that we saw before. Here is a link if you want to know more https://tinyurl.com/yr2h8tz7

1.3.1 separate

separate can be used to split a column based on a character. Here will use the yaounde dataframe.

yaounde <- 
  read_csv(file = here("chapter_xxx_tidy_data/data/yaounde_covid_seroprev_dataset.csv"), show_col_types = FALSE)

yaounde <- 
  yaounde %>%
  select("id_quest", "n_hhld_rooms", "n_hhld_adults", "n_hhld_children") %>%
  slice(2:25)

The column âid_questâ contains the unique identifier for each participant in the study. As you can see, âid_questâ contains multiple information separated by the character â/â. For instance, if we look at the first row (CARRIERE/NUM/002/0001), the respective information are the âareaâ (CARRIERE), the metric (NUM), the family code (002) and (0001) is the number of individuals within the family

What if we want to have that information separated into different columns? We can simply use the function separate()

yaounde <-
  yaounde %>%
  separate(col = id_quest,                
           into = c("area", "metric", "family", "individuals"))

yaounde
## # A tibble: 24 x 7
##    area     metric family individuals n_hhld_rooms n_hhld_adults n_hhld_children
##    <chr>    <chr>  <chr>  <chr>              <dbl>         <dbl>           <dbl>
##  1 CARRIERE NUM    002    0001                   2             3               1
##  2 CARRIERE NUM    002    0002                   2             3               1
##  3 CARRIERE NUM    038    0002                   5             2               4
##  4 CARRIERE NUM    038    0006                   5             2               4
##  5 CARRIERE NUM    015    0002                   4             6               1
##  6 CARRIERE NUM    005    0002                   4             2               2
##  7 BRIQUET~ NUM    012    0001                   5             8               4
##  8 BRIQUET~ NUM    019    0004                   7             7               1
##  9 CARRIERE NUM    014    0004                   4             5               0
## 10 BRIQUET~ NUM    014    0006                   4             6               0
## # ... with 14 more rows

Now the âid_questâ is separated into 4 different columns. The attribute where we specify the column we want to separate is col, and we define the new column names in into.

Noteworthy, if the vector inside into contains less or more elements than the columns expected after the separation an error will be printed.

By default, separate uses all the non-alphanumeric characters to separate a column i.e.

  • .

  • ,

  • _

  • -

  • /

  • :

Sometimes this might not be the case, and separate() allows you to choose the separator with the argument sep. For instance, you might want to split the âmetricâ column into 2 columns separating it by the letter âUâ

yaounde <-
  yaounde %>%
  separate(col = metric,
           sep = "U",
           into = c("x", "y"))

yaounde
## # A tibble: 24 x 8
##    area        x     y     family individuals n_hhld_rooms n_hhld_adults
##    <chr>       <chr> <chr> <chr>  <chr>              <dbl>         <dbl>
##  1 CARRIERE    N     M     002    0001                   2             3
##  2 CARRIERE    N     M     002    0002                   2             3
##  3 CARRIERE    N     M     038    0002                   5             2
##  4 CARRIERE    N     M     038    0006                   5             2
##  5 CARRIERE    N     M     015    0002                   4             6
##  6 CARRIERE    N     M     005    0002                   4             2
##  7 BRIQUETERIE N     M     012    0001                   5             8
##  8 BRIQUETERIE N     M     019    0004                   7             7
##  9 CARRIERE    N     M     014    0004                   4             5
## 10 BRIQUETERIE N     M     014    0006                   4             6
## # ... with 14 more rows, and 1 more variable: n_hhld_children <dbl>

One last chance to separate the columns is before or after a certain number of characters. Here below we want to separate the âareaâ column in order to retain the first 3 initials

yaounde <-
  yaounde %>%
  separate(col = area,
           sep = 3,
           into = c("a", "b"))

yaounde

## 10 BRI   QUETERIE N     M     014    0006                   4             6

defining sep = 3 the function will consider the first 3 elements from the left to make the separation. It is also possible to use a negative number that will make the function count starting from the last character

yaounde <-
  yaounde %>%
  separate(col = b,
           sep = -2,
           into = c("b", "c"))

1.3.2 unite

As we can separate columns, we can also unite columns with the unite() function. Letâs unite again the x and y columns into the âmetricâ column

yaounde <-
  yaounde %>%
  unite(col = "metric",
        x, y,
        sep = "U")

yaounde
## # A tibble: 24 x 9
##    a     b      c     metric family individuals n_hhld_rooms n_hhld_adults
##    <chr> <chr>  <chr> <chr>  <chr>  <chr>              <dbl>         <dbl>
##  1 CAR   RIE    RE    NUM    002    0001                   2             3
##  2 CAR   RIE    RE    NUM    002    0002                   2             3
##  3 CAR   RIE    RE    NUM    038    0002                   5             2
##  4 CAR   RIE    RE    NUM    038    0006                   5             2
##  5 CAR   RIE    RE    NUM    015    0002                   4             6
##  6 CAR   RIE    RE    NUM    005    0002                   4             2
##  7 BRI   QUETER IE    NUM    012    0001                   5             8
##  8 BRI   QUETER IE    NUM    019    0004                   7             7
##  9 CAR   RIE    RE    NUM    014    0004                   4             5
## 10 BRI   QUETER IE    NUM    014    0006                   4             6
## # ... with 14 more rows, and 1 more variable: n_hhld_children <dbl>

Now, the argument col defines the new column name after the union of the other columns (x and y in this example). Here the sep argument is used to define the character that will separate the new column values and its default is â_â. If you donât want a separator you can define it as an empty space i.e.Â sep = ââ.

yaounde <-
  yaounde %>%
  unite(col = "dafa",
        n_hhld_rooms, n_hhld_adults,
        sep = "")

yaounde
## # A tibble: 24 x 8

1.3.2.1 exercise 1

Now a small exercise. The aim is to use the unite() function to reverse engineering the yaounde dataframe and bring it back to the original state when you just uploaded it. In other words you have to rebuild the âid_questâ column.

1.3.2.2 exercise 2

re-upload the yaounde dataframe

yaounde <- read_csv(file = here(âchapter_xxx_tidy_data/data/yaounde_covid_seroprev_dataset.csvâ), show_col_types = FALSE)

and select only the columns âid_questâ and ân_hhld_childrenâ. Now, you should have a dataframe with only 2 columns. Your objective is to turn the dataframe in wide format having the family id as columns (e.g.Â the first âid_questâ is CARRIERE/NUM/013/0001 and the family code is 013).
